SIMPLE: pickerel
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pickerel
<hw>Pick"er*el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Dim. of
<er>Pike</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>pickerell</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A young or small
pike.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bet [better] is, quoth he, a pike than a <qex>pickerel</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any one of several
species of freshwater fishes of the genus <gen>Esox</gen>, esp. the
smaller species.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The glasseye, or wall-eyed
pike. See <er>Wall-eye</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The federation, or chain, pickerel (<spn>Esox
reticulatus</spn>) and the brook pickerel (<spn>Esox Americanus</spn>)
are the most common American species. They are used for food, and are
noted for their voracity. About the Great Lakes the pike is called
<xex>pickerel</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pickerel weed</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a
blue-flowered aquatic plant (<spn>Pontederia cordata</spn>) having large
arrow-shaped leaves. So called because common in slow-moving waters
where pickerel are often found.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pickering</ent>⟦br⟧
